        <!-- Case Study -->
        <div class="case-study-civil-war">
            <h3>üìã Case Study: Confederate Officer's Sword Authentication & Restoration</h3>
            <p><strong>Artifact:</strong> Family-owned Confederate officer's sword attributed to a local military officer, 15th Virginia Infantry, recovered from Spotsylvania battlefield area in 1920s.</p>

            <p><strong>Authentication Challenges:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>Sword blade heavily corroded with illegible maker's marks</li>
                <li>Guard and pommel showed period-inappropriate modifications</li>
                <li>Family provenance stories contained historical inaccuracies</li>
                <li>Previous "restoration" had altered original finish</li>
                <li>No documented chain of custody since 1920s recovery</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>Our Comprehensive Process:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>Electrolytic reduction revealed original "Leech & Rigdon" maker's marks</li>
                <li>Materials analysis confirmed period-appropriate steel composition</li>
                <li>Military records research verified the officer's service at Spotsylvania</li>
                <li>Genealogical research confirmed family ownership timeline</li>
                <li>Conservation treatment stabilized corrosion without altering patina</li>
                <li>Created comprehensive provenance documentation with battlefield context</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>Result:</strong> Authenticated as genuine 1862 Leech & Rigdon officer's sword, restored to museum exhibition standards, appraised value increased from $2,000 to $15,000, comprehensive provenance documentation provided.</p>

            <blockquote style="border-left: 4px solid #8D6E63; padding-left: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; font-style: italic;">
                "Prism Specialties not only saved our family's Civil War sword but proved its incredible historical significance. The authentication process was thorough and professional, and the restoration is museum quality. We now know our ancestor's story with certainty." - Local family, Fredericksburg, VA
            </blockquote>
        </div>

